Hope to get a help from you to be part of this amazing event :)
lender.occupational_info: University of Connecticut UNESCO Chair & Institute of Comparative Human Rights Amii Omara-Otunnu, D. Phil. (Oxon) UNESCO Chair-holder & Executive Director An Equal Opportunity Employer 233 Glenbrook Road Unit 4124 Storrs, Connecticut 06269-4124 Telephone: (860)486-0647 Fascimile: (860)486-2545 e-mail: unescochair@uconn.edu web: ww.unescochair.uconn.edu May 31, 2011 Re: Sponsorship of Human Rights Leader – Farah Abou El Sel Warm Greetings, I write to inform you that a young human rights leader from Lebanon has been selected and has fulfilled all registration requirements to participate in the 2011 International Leadership Programme: A Global Intergenerational Training Forum, sponsored by the UNESCO Chair & Institute of Comparative Human Rights. Farah Abou El Sel from Lebanon has been selected from a pool of over 700 applicants from more than 85 nations and representing all 6 continents, to participate in the Forum from August 5 - August 14, 2011 on the University of Connecticut campus in Storrs, Connecticut, USA. The Forum, apart from providing young leaders with skills and tools to be effective in their various areas of advocacy and promotion of human rights, aims to present the participants with a human face of the United States and to foster understanding between the people of this country and other regions of the world. The UNESCO Chair & Institute of Comparative Human Rights will provide all Forum participants with housing, meals, ground transportation in Connecticut during the Forum, as well as resource materials and a certificate of participation. As you are aware, air travel from most countries to the United States is quite costly. As such, most of the participants especially those traveling from developing nations will find it extremely impossible to bear the costs of air travel. Thus I would like to appeal to you to consider assisting partially, or sponsoring in whole the air travel for this outstanding young human rights leader from Lebanon. I hope you share the view that human rights is a means of cultivating cooperation between the US and other parts of the world and will consider assisting and facilitating this participant in attending the Forum. Please feel free to contact me with any questions you might have about the Forum, or anything else regarding this matter. Thank you for your consideration, Amii Omara-Otunnu, D. Phil. (Oxon.), UNESCO Chair-holder & Executive Director, Executive Director, UConn-ANC Partnership, Professor of History
